We recommended that management:
a. Direct the financial and Municipal Assessor to prepare a financial and operational plan and requirements to carry out the tax mapping;
b. Enjoin the Sangguniang Bayan to support funding initiatives for the preparation of tax maps and subsequent related activities thereto.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
Direct the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to:
a.1.   Reconcile the PPE balance of CY 2023 RPCPPE and the Statement of Financial Position (FS) as of December 31, 2023;
a.2.  Facilitate the preparation of the PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, and reconcile the same, in accordance with Sections 119 and 120, Chapter 7 of the NGAS Manual; and
a.3.  Request for additional manpower, when warranted and feasible, to assist in the preparation and reconciliation of PPE records and reports;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary journal 
entries to:
b.1. Reflect the correct Depreciation Expense and Accumulated Depreciation by considering the salvage value of PPEs and correct depreciable amount, in accordance with to Paragraph 71 of IPSAS 17 and PAG 6 of IPSAS 17;
b.2. Reclassify tangible items with acquisition cost of more than ₱50,000.00 recorded under the liability and expense accounts to PPE accounts in compliance with the capitalization threshold of COA Circular No. 2022-004;
b.3. Reclassify tangible items with acquisition cost of less than ₱50,000.00 initially classified as PPE to semi-expendable properties and the related accumulated depreciation to be closed in the books of accounts in accordance with Item Nos. 4.2 and 4.3 of COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022; and
Require the Inventory Committee to complete the one-time cleansing of the PPE in accordance with the procedures of Commission on Audit (COA) Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended that management:
Direct the Municipal Assessor to prepare a financial and operational plan and requirements to carry out the tax mapping;
Enjoin the Sangguniang Bayan to support funding initiatives for the preparation of tax maps and subsequent related activities thereto.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
Ensure that only properties that are considered useful and practicable, especially for intended beneficiaries, are purchased as planned to avoid losses from deterioration of idle PPE;
Create a Disposal Committee in accordance with Section 79 of P.D. No. 1445, to determine the serviceability of PPEs and facilitate the disposal process of the unserviceable properties;
Direct the Disposal Committee to prepare the Waste Material Report (WMR) and the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) in consonance with Section 125 of NGAS Volume I; and
Instruct the General Services Officer/ Municipal Treasurer to request in writing for the disposal of unserviceable properties, to the Office of the Auditor, in adherence with Section 167 of COA Circular No. 92-386 dated October 22, 1992.

Based on the foregoing observations, we reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that:

the Municipal Mayor, thru the Municipal Engineer, provide explanation on the noted delays and always take appropriate action regarding the non-completion of the projects within the target completion date;

the Municipal Engineer (i) ensure that all the necessary reports/documents are properly prepared; (ii) observe strict compliance with the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184, specifically Annex E and COA Memorandum No. 2005-027 dated February 27, 2005 in the grant of time extensions; and (iii) carefully evaluate the implementation of infrastructure projects; 

the Municipal Accountant, as the internal auditor, see to it that all the necessary documentary requirements attached to the vouchers are accurate and complete before processing the claims; and

the concerned offices submit all the lacking documents to the Audit Team and henceforth, ensure compliance with pertinent rules and regulations relative to disbursements for infrastructure projects including the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 to avoid suspension and even disallowance in audit.

We recommended that:

The Municipal Mayor along with the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator and Municipal Engineer strictly adhere to the provisions of DILG-DBM JMC No. 2017-1 in the planning and implementation of the  programs/projects/activities funded under the 20 percent Development Fund;

The Municipal Mayor and the Municipal Accountant see to it that goods are delivered on time.  Imposed liquidated damages on the failure to deliver goods on the specific date indicated in the POs pursuant to Section 8 of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184;

The Municipal Mayor instruct the (i) Municipal  Engineer to include the cost of hauling and freight of materials for projects to be undertaken by administration in the Program of Works; and (ii) personnel in charge of the preparation of the PO to properly indicate the place where the goods are to be delivered by the supplier; and

The Municipal Accountant (i) see to it that all the necessary documentary requirements attached to the vouchers are accurate and complete before processing the claims; and (ii) prepare adjusting accounting entries to correct the deficiency noted in the recording of transactions.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Instruct the Inventory Committee and all concerned offices to conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts of the Municipality in                   accordance with the prescribed procedures embodied in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to establish PPE balances that are         verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability;
Provide additional manpower at the Office of the Municipal Treasurer to aide the Municipal Treasurer in the supply and property management of the LGU;
After the conduct of inventory taking, direct the inventory committee to prepare and submit the following to the Audit Team in the prescribed format:
Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE);
Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), if there are unserviceable properties found during inventory taking;
Request for Relief from Accountability by Accountable persons for lost PPE items under their accountability, if any;
Journal Entry Vouchers drawn by the Accounting Unit for recognition of loss of PPE from concerned accountable officers/personnel, if any, and other necessary adjusting entries.

We have recommended that management:
Direct the designated Inspection Officer to conduct post-repair              inspection of all its government vehicles subjected to repairs;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer, in the absence of a General Services Office (GSO), to reconstruct and maintain a repair history on this regard;
Completely accomplish the Waste Material Report particularly on the disposition of the waste materials and ensure completeness of the       supporting documents for repairs of government vehicles.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
require the GAD Focal Person to comply with PCW Memorandum Circular No. 2020-05 dated September 11, 2020 in the attribution of the GAD Budget;
through its GAD Focal Point System (GFPS), exhaust all available resources for the collection and processing of data requirements of the GAD Database as required under Section B (1) of the Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01 to serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation;
require the MHO, MSWDO and the Municipal Accountant to ensure that claims against the GAD fund are properly supported with required documents to prove the regularity and legality of the subject disbursements; and
require the BAC to strengthen internal control over the evaluation of bids and post-qualification of bidders.

Based on the foregoing observations, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
Municipal Accountant to prepare and the MDRRMO to submit the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF on or before the 15th day after the end of each month to the Audit Team as required under Item 5.1.5 of COA Circular No. 2012-002.
BAC to (i) strictly adhere to the requirements of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 for the procurement of goods and services charged against the LDRRMF; and (ii) furnish the Audit Team with a copy of the Purchase Order and its attachments within five (5) working days from the issuance as required under Section 3.2.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001;
MDRRMO and the Municipal Accountant to submit written explanation/justification and/or submit the required lacking documents to prove the regularity and legality of the subject disbursements;
Personnel in charge of preparing the PO to provide reasonable lead time in the delivery of procured items, taking into consideration the geographical location of the Municipality and other concerns raised by the suppliers.  Failure to comply after considering the possible causes of delay shall warrant the Municipal Accountant and Acting Municipal Treasurer to impose the corresponding liquidated damages on delayed deliveries of goods; and
Municipal Accountant to (i) adhere strictly to the accounting and reporting guidelines for LDRRMF set forth in COA Circular No. 2012-002 specifically on the transfer of unutilized LDRRMF; (ii) review the regularity and completeness of supporting documents of disbursement vouchers before processing the claims; and (iii) prepare adjusting accounting entries to correct the deficiency noted in the recording of transactions.

We have recommended that management consider the following:

Direct the management to prioritize and to fast tract the completion of the LGU’s P/P/As mentioned above;

Direct all officials and employees responsible for the conduct of procurement activity, including the end-users, to meticulously and judiciously plan the procurement;

Direct the management to send a written demand to the supplier/contractor for the full and satisfactory performance of their obligations under their respective contract with the municipal government;

Direct the management to enforce the provisions in the contract particularly the aspect on liquidated damages in congruence with the provisions on liquidated damages under R.A. 9184; and

Evaluate the LGU’s capability to undertake projects by administration and take appropriate actions.

We have reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendation that management:

Requiring the Municipal Collectors to demand a duly approved Requisition Slip from the customers/private contractors before processing rental payments;

Instructing the Motorpool In-Charge to approve time records indicated in trip tickets filled-up by customers;

Directing the Municipal Engineer/ Municipal Agriculturist, and the   GSO to conduct pre and post-inspection for every lease transaction;

Requiring the GSO to verify details of trip tickets vis-à-vis the amount paid and require the contractor for payment of deficiencies, if there’s any;


Instructing the GSO to maintain custody of equipment keys;

Executing a lease contract with a contractor to cover the terms and conditions of the lease agreement;

Instructing concerned offices to maintain equipment logbooks; and

Directing the Municipal Treasurer to set income targets and prepare separate income reporting for monitoring purposes.

1.  Exert all efforts to identify the recipients and exhaust all means to find any paper trail of the disbursements.

2.  Require the Implementing Agency to immediately submit the liquidation reports   and  refund the unutilized fund transfers for completed projects, if any;

3. If found untraceable, and after all effort are already exerted and still cannot be identified agency must apply for write off .

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

require the GAD Focal Person to be guided by COA Circular No. 2012-003 dated October 29, 2012 relative to irregular, unnecessary, excessive, extravagant and unconscionable (IUEEU) expenditures in the implementation of GAD programs;

require the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) to spearhead the setting up and maintenance of the GAD database to serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation;

remind the MSWDO to refrain from procuring goods or supplies on reimbursement basis;

require the MSWDO and the Municipal Accountant to submit written explanation/justification and/or the required lacking documents to prove the regularity and legality of the subject disbursements; and

require the BAC to submit written explanation/justification on inconsistencies noted in the procedures undertaken relative to the procurement of snacks for the women’s group meeting and submit copy of Purchase Order and its attachments within five calendar days from issuance thereof.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the BAC to:

furnish the Audit Team with a copy of the Contract of Agreement and its attachments within five working days from execution thereof as required under Section 3.1.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 23, 2009;

observe strictly the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 to ensure adherence to the principles of transparency, competitiveness and public monitoring; 



strengthen internal control over the evaluation of bids and post-qualification of bidders; and

submit the lacking documents cited above to the Audit Team to comply with the requirements of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and address the deficiencies enumerated.

We recommended that the Management:

Conduct regular monitoring on the implementation of the plan and other relevant laws within the Municipality’s jurisdiction to ensure the viability and effectiveness of the solid waste management programs;



Designate SWM Coordinator who will be the implementing arm of the municipality’s SWM plan and who shall directly supervise all solid waste operations and activities of the municipality;

Require other barangays to re-establish and effectively maintain their MRFs and encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of wastes;

Reconstitute the membership of the SWMB to conform to the membership requirement of RA 9003 and to optimize the involvement of civil society as envisioned in the law.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:
MDRRMO to prepare LDRRMIP in accordance with COA Circular No. 2012-02;
BAC, BAC Secretariat and Accounting Office to i) submit the lacking documents and/or explanations for the issues indicated in paragraphs 12.11, 12.16, 12.17 and 12.21; and ii) adhere with the GPPB Circular 2020-01 concerning emergency procurement of goods and the revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 on the conduct of public bidding;
Office who was assigned to distribute the COVID-19 related items to submit list of recipients with important details such as the actual quantity received, signature of the recipients, date received and Office/location of recipients for the proper evaluation of the related disbursements;
Concerned Office in the preparation of PRs, POs and AIRs to indicate description of items for the proper evaluation of procurements; and
Municipal Accountant to check and ensure the completeness of documents before effecting payment.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive together with other members of the MDRRMC:

4.1.	Strictly adhere to the guidelines set under the pertinent sections of JMC No. 2013-1 in the appropriation and utilization of the LDRRMF by not charging the expenses related to the repairs and maintenance of the vehicle and other maintenance and operating expenses to the said fund;

4.2.	Stop using LDRRM Fund in procuring equipment which are not among those enumerated in the said JMC and in the DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2012-73;

4.3.	Instruct the members of the Inspectorate Team to see to it that item/s delivered are personally checked/inspected by them and that all specifications written in the documents are present and the same as the one’s purchased and delivered by the supplier; and

4.4.	Instruct the MDRRM staff and responders not to lend/use the equipment in any other activity and to take good care those equipment/supplies so that it will be readily available in case of calamity/emergency.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the HRMO and other responsible officials and employees:

6.1.	Strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2009-001 by furnishing the COA Office copies of all the contracts in hiring JOs and COS together with its supporting documents within five working days from execution thereof;

6.2.	See to it that the duties and responsibilities/scoop of work of each JO are stipulated in a specific manner in the contract and make sure that all JOs sign in it confirming/agreeing with all the terms and conditions;

6.3.	Ensure that all the supporting documents attached to the DV are properly accomplished and signed by the concerned person; and

6.4.	Prepare a monthly work/duty scheme that provides a day or two rest day in a week for each responder/staff but ensure that there is somebody left to oversee the office and in case all the responders or those not on duty needs to standby, a memorandum from the LCE requiring them to report for duty will form part of their DTRs supporting documents.

17.1.	Official/employee assigned to approve the DTTs to see to it that all data needed be accomplished, specifically the vehicle plate number and passenger/s name;

17.2.	Drivers to advise their passenger/s to affix their signatures in the approved DTTs after the trip; and

17.3.	Monthly reports related to fuel consumption submitted to the COA for audit.

