We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

34.1. Require the Administrative Officials authorizing the travels and the Drivers to properly accomplish and serially number the Driver’s Trip Tickets;

34.2.  Designate an LGU employee to prepare and submit the Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption;

34.3. Instruct the concerned LGU employees to adopt the prescribed format of the Driver’s Trip Ticket, Requisition and Issue Voucher, Monthly Report of Official Travel, Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption; and diligently observe the pertinent provisions of COA Circular No. 77-61.

We recommended and the management agreed that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to:

exert extra effort to account for the unreconciled difference appearing in the bank statements and financial statements and to faithfully present the correct balances of the accounts;

prepare the necessary adjusting entries to record and correct the unrecorded amounts and erroneous entries made in the Cash in Bank account, respectively; 

revert to proper Cash in Bank and payable accounts all stale checks;

if possible, coordinate with the bank to determine whether checks claimed by the payees were not yet presented for payment.  Secure the addresses of the payees for notification of the return of stale checks in their possession for replacement;

for checks which have been stale for many years and that sufficient documents show that obligations no longer exist, consider the reversion of these payables to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund; and

henceforth, send written notice to the payees one month before the check becomes stale.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to instruct the BAC to:

furnish the Audit Team with a copy of the Contract of Agreement and its attachments within five working days from the execution thereof as required under Section 3.1.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 23, 2009;

observe strictly the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 to ensure adherence to the principles of transparency, competitiveness and public monitoring;

submit the lacking documents cited above to the Audit Team to comply with the requirements of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and address the deficiencies enumerated; and 

prepare the required reports/documents with extra care to avoid errors which could mislead readers and users of the reports.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to require the Municipal Budget Officer and Accountant to:

submit a satisfactory explanation on the recording of blind obligations noted by the Audit Team;

effect the necessary adjustment/s by reverting to the general fund the amount obligated as payables without proper documentation;

ensure that obligations are recorded only when goods are already delivered and services are rendered to the Municipality; and

record obligations only when they are duly supported with documents to support their validity and existence.

